{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17640284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17640284"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:14:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:14:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17814"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17814"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.04,0,0.08,0.83]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10528"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72946"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10528","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10528"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17814"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58416"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9888"},{"type":"tags","id":"9924"},{"type":"tags","id":"9925"},{"type":"tags","id":"9929"},{"type":"tags","id":"9930"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24572"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24812"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72946","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72946"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPeripheral chemoreceptors play a vital role in maintaining respiratory homeostasis by monitoring blood gas levels and adjusting ventilation accordingly.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of peripheral chemoreceptors?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Measure carbon dioxide in brain tissue","Monitor cerebrospinal fluid pH","Sense blood glucose concentration","Respond to changes in blood pressure","Detect changes in arterial oxygen levels"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of peripheral chemoreceptors is to \u003Cstrong\u003Edetect changes in arterial oxygen levels\u003C/strong\u003E. Located in the carotid and aortic bodies, these specialised sensors respond within seconds to decreases in arterial oxygen tension, triggering increased ventilation through afferent signals to the respiratory centres.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasure carbon dioxide in brain tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - Central chemoreceptors in the medulla are responsible for detecting carbon dioxide levels in brain tissue, not peripheral chemoreceptors.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonitor cerebrospinal fluid pH\u003C/strong\u003E - Central chemoreceptors in the medulla monitor cerebrospinal fluid pH, while peripheral chemoreceptors primarily monitor blood oxygen levels.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESense blood glucose concentration\u003C/strong\u003E - Although carotid bodies have some sensitivity to blood glucose levels, this is not their primary physiological role in respiratory control.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERespond to changes in blood pressure\u003C/strong\u003E - Baroreceptors, not chemoreceptors, are specialised to detect and respond to changes in blood pressure.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile peripheral chemoreceptors can also detect changes in arterial carbon dioxide and pH, their primary and most sensitive function is oxygen sensing. The carotid bodies provide approximately 80% of the peripheral chemoreceptor response, with aortic bodies contributing the remainder.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Peripheral chemoreceptors in the carotid and aortic bodies primarily detect changes in arterial oxygen levels.","Peripheral chemoreceptors respond rapidly to decreased arterial oxygen, increasing ventilation within seconds.","The carotid bodies provide approximately 80% of the peripheral chemoreceptor response."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58416"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17814"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58416"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T21:48:30+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T21:49:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10528"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72946"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"